The crisis PR handbook, says Scott Galloway (https://twitter.com/profgallow=
ay/status/976454703788720128), has three essential steps: The person in cha=
rge responds, takes full responsibility for whatever went wrong, and overco=
rrects for the problem.=C2=A0

The canonical example is Tylenol in 1982. Seven people died after ingesting=
 corrupted capsules laced with cyanide (http://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/23/y=
our-money/tylenol-made-a-hero-of-johnson-johnson-the-recall-that-started.ht=
ml), threatening to tarnish the brand forever. James Burke, then CEO of Tyl=
enol manufacturer Johnson &amp;amp; Johnson, spent $100 million to recall a=
ll 31 million bottles of the painkiller then on the shelf. It created a tam=
perproof bottle and returned Tylenol to the shelves two months later. Withi=
n a year, Tylenol had recaptured nearly all of its market share.

Facebook's response to the Cambridge Analytica scandal has been less decisi=
ve. The person in charge, Mark Zuckerberg, waited five days to respond. Whe=
n he did=C2=A0post his much-anticipated note on Facebook (https://www.faceb=
ook.com/zuck/posts/10104712037900071) he took responsibility but did not, a=
s commentators were quick to note, apologize. And while the company laid ou=
t a plan to &quot;crack down on platform abuse (https://newsroom.fb.com/new=
s/2018/03/cracking-down-on-platform-abuse/),&quot; instituting new restrict=
ions on developers' ongoing access to user data, it felt like less of an ov=
ercorrection and more like an overdue set of tweaks.

At the very least, today's moves will bring to an end the drumbeat of &quot=
;Where's Mark?&quot; stories, which had grown deafening. The moves to tight=
en up developer access to user data are welcome. In the short term, they ma=
y stop the bleeding.=C2=A0

But as my colleague Russell Brandom pointed out today (https://twitter.com/=
russellbrandom/status/976498903188156417), Facebook sits in the center of t=
hree related but distinct crises. There's the data privacy scandal, crystal=
ized by the Cambridge Analytica revelations. There's the information integr=
ity crisis, playing out daily in the News Feed. And there's the broader cul=
tural reckoning over how we spend our time on social media and whether its =
long-term effects are ultimately harmful, both personally and societally.

As a Digiday piece noted today (https://digiday.com/marketing/facebook-tota=
lly-screwed-facebook-bungled-response-cambridge-analytica-crisis/), Faceboo=
k now sits in what crisis public-relations experts call a &quot;convergence=
&quot;: &quot;a list of seemingly unrelated problems and multiple negative =
storylines that all get tied together.&quot; And as I wrote yesterday (http=
s://www.theverge.com/2018/3/20/17140490/facebook-cambridge-analytica-data-c=
risis), Facebook has lost control of the narrative because it can no longer=
 convincingly say it has control of the platform.=C2=A0

In January, Zuckerberg wrote that fixing Facebook's platform would be his p=
ersonal challenge for the year (https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/4/16849646/=
mark-zuckerberg-personal-challenge-2018-fix-facebook-harassment-election-in=
terference). But as he wades into this latest crisis, five days after it be=
gan, it's not clear his company is bringing all its resources to bear. And =
as #deletefacebook begins to trend around the world (http://www.newsweek.co=
m/cambridge-analytica-deletefacebook-trending-end-social-network-zuckerberg=
-852322), the challenge of fixing the platform feels greater than ever.

[Zuckerberg is set to speak with CNN tonight. We'll have a full account of =
that in tomorrow's edition.]


